<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="103" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,150,1005]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,330,356]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Very small, wing length 
<quantity box="[610,742,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" metricValueMax="3.2" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" unit="mm" value="2.8" valueMax="3.2" valueMin="2.4">2.4‒3.2mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis box="[753,820,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Male:</emphasis>
Arista short-pubescent, longest branches less than 1.5 times greatest width of arista. Frons nearly horizontal, broad and flat, in dorsal aspect wholly velvety black in contrast to silvery white parafacial plates. Fronto-orbital plate with 2 short orbital setae and 2 frontal setae. Frons and facial margin equally projecting. Mesonotum extensively dark brown pruinose, postpronotal lobes and notopleura silvery grey and a pair of spots near at scutellum light grey. Dorsocentral setae 3 behind suture; acrostichal field with setulae only, arranged in 2‒3 irregular rows. Mid femur with 1 subapical 
<emphasis box="[983,1011,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">pd</emphasis>
seta, without 
<emphasis box="[1171,1197,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">pv</emphasis>
setae; mid tibia with 1 
<emphasis box="[173,201,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">pd</emphasis>
seta at middle. Hind femur with 1 
<emphasis box="[595,621,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">av</emphasis>
seta near apex, without 
<emphasis box="[896,922,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">pv</emphasis>
setae. Tergite VI merged with prehypopygeal sclerite. Sternite I bare. Sternite V and hypopygium as in 
<figureCitation box="[787,911,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[195,1369,205,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[187,1401,179,1917]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Limnophora beckeri (Stein) (A‒C), L. bipunctata (Stein) (D‒G). Males. Hypopygium, caudal (A, D) and lateral (B, E); sternite V (C, G); sternites I and II (F). Same scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4671810" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4671810/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Figs 1A‒C</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis box="[922,1015,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Female:</emphasis>
Similar to the male, but frons slightly convex and declining; frontal triangle matt shining, demarcated from velvety black frontal vitta. Dark brown area on mesonotum restricted to a narrow median stripe, a pair of subtriangular marks in front of the suture, a broad band immediately behind the suture and all scutellum. Ovipositor with hind marginal setae on tergite VII forming a complete row, not interrupted laterally as in other examined species. See 
<tableCitation box="[921,1004,727,753]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="6.[151,214,575,601]" captionTargetBox="[159,1920,612,1616]" captionTargetId="graphics-40@6.[151,1932,752,1617]" captionText="Table 1. Matrix of 11 characters and their states (different colours) derived from the ovipositor and scored for 12 species of Limnophora." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF496603027CFFDB57B3FDBAF984772C" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" tableUuid="DF496603027CFFDB57B3FDBAF984772C">Table 1</tableCitation>
for more ovipositor characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="103" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,150,1005]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,762,788]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Distribution.</emphasis>
Canary Islands: Gran Canaria, Tenerife, La Gomera, La Palma. Originally considered endemic to the Canary Islands, but Hennig (1964) recorded it from 
<collectingCountry box="[816,865,799,825]" name="Iran" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Iran</collectingCountry>
: Sistan &amp; Baluchestan province, Iranshahr county. 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang, C. &amp; Xue, W." box="[151,393,835,862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" pagination="189 - 204" refId="ref18715" refString="Zhang, C. &amp; Xue, W. (1996) Faunistical studies on the genus Limnophora in China (Diptera: Muscidae). Entomologica sinica, 3 (3), 189 - 204. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1744 - 7917.1996. tb 00267. x" type="journal article" year="1996">Zhang &amp; Xue (1996)</bibRefCitation>
further reported 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[590,704,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis box="[590,704,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">L. beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[777,848,835,861]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">China</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion box="[861,960,835,861]" country="China" name="Guizhou" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Guizhou</collectingRegion>
, included the species in a key to Chinese 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robineau-Desvoidy" authorityYear="1830" box="[151,289,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,289,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Limnophora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males, and illustrated the male terminalia (figs 10‒12). The Chinese taxon is indeed very similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[151,264,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis box="[151,264,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">L. beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but should be treated as a distinct species on basis of differences in the male terminalia, especially the proportions of the cerci. 
<bibRefCitation author="Stein, P." box="[424,562,943,969]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" pagination="147 - 244" refId="ref18652" refString="Stein, P. (1918) Zur weitern Kenntnis aussereuropaeischer Anthomyiden. Annales historico-naturales Musei nationalis hungarici, 16, 147 - 244." type="journal article" year="1918">Stein (1918)</bibRefCitation>
recorded 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stein" authorityYear="1908" box="[672,893,943,969]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Calliophrys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beckeri">
<emphasis box="[672,893,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Calliophrys beckeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[959,1041,943,969]" name="Taiwan" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
(“Formosa”). The species involved is expectedly identical with the species found in Guizhou.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
